<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-logarithms-of-products-and-ratios" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Logarithms of Products and Ratios</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_9d8x2840">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_oazgfz1j">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_m407vz1n">
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qlhhusgb">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_kxuei5yj">
                        1.2 Indices and Logarithms
                    </p>
                 </li>
                  <li xml:id="auto_ij2re4i1">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_p40wf0zv">
                        1.1 Real Numbers
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_42x8xke2">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p xml:id="auto_gnldlo6p">
                        Apply common logarithms in multiplication, division, powers and roots of numbers
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bgx06oq2" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_nscdkgig">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8vb4kkkk" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_zqs78u0a">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
       
    </objectives>

    <!-- <p xml:id="auto_1jds6diu">
        Since logarithms are exponents, the laws that guide indices also apply to logarithms. In this section, we explore how to simplify the logarithms of products and ratios.
    </p>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Multiplication and division using logarithms</title>
            
        <p xml:id="auto_08rh4k8z">
            Logarithms simplify multiplication and division by converting them into addition and subtraction, respectively. This is particularly useful when dealing with large numbers.
        </p>

        <example xml:id="auto_c2we0tmk">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_w4nnylu8">
                    Find <m>236.5 \times 42.8</m> using logarithm table.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_wlpapwzd">
                    Find the logarithm of each number from the logarithm table:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_mzmokdh4">
                    <me>
                        \log 236.5 = 2.3741, \quad \log 42.8 = 1.6318
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_m0naf8xu">
                    Add the logarithms:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_d0x91q8l">
                    <me>
                        2.3741 + 1.6318 = 4.0059
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_5d20m6yo">
                    Find the antilogarithm of <m>4.0059</m>:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ve412q0v">
                    <me>
                        \text{Antilog} (4.0059) \approx 10160
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_glxjj6j0">
                    Thus, <m>236.5 \times 42.8 \approx 10160</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="auto_6vubc9x6">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_qu13c392">
                    Find <m>\frac{528.6}{24.7}</m> using logarithm tables.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_3ng4fcyd">
                    Find the logarithm of each number from the logarithm table:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_1wtm9h5a">
                    <me>
                        \log 528.6 = 2.7233, \quad \log 24.7 = 1.3927
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_nnfehooo">
                    Subtract the logarithms:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_jb5hkc01">
                    <me>
                        2.7233 - 1.3927 = 1.3306
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_9nv4vktz">
                    Find the antilogarithm of <m>1.3306</m>:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_bx63b3uo">
                    <me>
                        \text{Antilog} (1.3306) \approx 21.4
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_nfckc3qu">
                    Thus, <m>\frac{528.6}{24.7} \approx 21.4</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-multiplication-using-logarithm-tables">
            <title>Multiplication using logarithm tables</title>
            <stack label="stk-multiplication-using-logarithm-tables" source="stack/top/1-0-Numbers-Algebra/Indices-and-Logarithms/Logarithms/Multiplying-and-Dividing-Logarithms/Multiplication-using-logarithm-tables.xml"/>
        </exercise>

    </paragraphs>

    <activity xml:id="auto_ayhwdwhb">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_kd2gqbac">
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_yavb90ot">
                <term>Materials:</term> Paper and pen
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_klrpltt7">
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_uwrseg9k">Write <m>3^2 \times 3^4</m> in index form.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_su1ukh03">Express the result as a single power of <m>3</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8atpywe3">
                    Convert your result into logarithmic form.
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_h9qf7hx1">
                    Now separately write:
                    <m>\log_3 3^2 + \log_3 3^4</m>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3pmmrfq8">Compare the two results.</li>
            </ol>
            <p xml:id="auto_sl8k3pd2">
                What relationship do you observe?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight xml:id="auto_5iod4xc1">
        <p xml:id="auto_1j8i6nl6">
            The logarithm of a product is equal to the sum of the logarithms of the individual factors
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_dwvzljvg">
            Logarithms change multiplication into addition.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_85e1bj9r">
        Since:
        <me>
            3^2 \times 3^4 = 3^{2+4} = 3^6
        </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_rmf0j6po">
            Converting to logarithmic form:
        <me>
            \log_3 3^6 = 6
        </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wh5jvz2q">
            But:
        <me>
            \log_3 3^2 + \log_3 3^4 = 2 + 4 = 6
        </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ihnksfqb">
            Therefore,
        <me>
            \log_a (MN) = \log_a M + \log_a N
        </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vbdppdde">
            This is called the <term>Product Law of Logarithms</term>.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <activity xml:id="auto_qiryf1dh">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_t23271y9">
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_brzq9kh3">
                <term>Instruction:</term>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_v1a7emma">
                Repeat the process for division:
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_z0ga3gym">Write <m>5^6 \div 5^2</m> in index form.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_y6iaakw9">Express as a single power of <m>5</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lgxv78h4">Convert into logarithmic form.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5pqinubm">
                    Compare with:
                    <m>\log_5 5^6 - \log_5 5^2</m>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <insight xml:id="auto_dz5v46qx">
        <p xml:id="auto_2po2ef5u">
            The logarithm of a quotient (ratio) is equal to the difference between the logarithm of the numerator and the logarithm of the denominator
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_kz6w3g6j">
            Logarithms change division into subtraction.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_slfh949v">
            Since:
        <me>
            5^6 \div 5^2 = 5^{6-2} = 5^4
        </me>
        </p>

        <p xml:id="auto_iagdkbfn">
            Therefore,
        <me>
            \log_a \left(\frac{M}{N}\right) = \log_a M - \log_a N
        </me>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <example xml:id="auto_ua24bout">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_tzv7bbxs">
                Express the following as a single logarithm and evaluate:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_2gl8077k">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ed4y9akb"><m>\log_{10} 25 + \log_{10} 4</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_zkq9lo7u"><m>\log_{2} 48 - \log_{2} 3</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_2rw215ke"><m>\log_{10} 20 + \log_{10} 50</m></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_x75sxrm8">
                a) Using the product law: <me>\log_{10} (25 \times 4) = \log_{10} 100 = 2</me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_sol_b">
                b) Using the ratio law: <me>\log_{2} \left(\frac{48}{3}\right) = \log_{2} 16 = 4</me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_sol_c">
                c) <me>\log_{10} (20 \times 50) = \log_{10} 1000 = 3</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <exercises xml:id="auto_lf1ku6bz">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_lckgyfhz">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ipi5oypn">
                    Write each of the following as a single logarithm:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_xo2i1wwe">
                    <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_q4hvokk1"><m>\log_a 7 + \log_a 3</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_0dmxzi8v"><m>\log_x 24 - \log_x 4</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_gpux50e1"><m>\log_{10} 5 + \log_{10} 2</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_7p0yfti6"><m>\log_b 50 - \log_b 2</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_m2semums">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_d4m2wf2o"><m>\log_a 21</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_886yaow9"><m>\log_x 6</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ou7omflr"><m>\log_{10} 10 = 1</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_j66bmnii"><m>\log_b 25</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_h8c19ix9">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_i5v97lj0">
                    Simplify the following:
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ulnswh6d"><m>\log_3 27 + \log_3 9</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_84ksjow9"><m>\log_5 125 - \log_5 5</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_zaxoital"><m>\log_2 32 - \log_2 4</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_xkxlf5m3"><m>\log_7 49 + \log_7 7</m></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_28qv5d73">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_q6usja6t"><m>5</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_bgq37tbv"><m>2</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_1mcr0vne"><m>3</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_milg8g3z"><m>3</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises> -->

<xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <activity xml:id="auto_intro_logs_products">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_x8dhwyfd">
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_a0szgmvd">
                <term>Materials:</term> Paper, pen, and calculator.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_r4gwf8vn">
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_eedkn5qy">Evaluate: <m>2^2 \times 2^3</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ft2lvfp5">Rewrite the result as a single power of <m>2</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_baw2c677">Find: <m>\log_2 (2^2 \times 2^3)</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qmi501lr">Compare with: <m>\log_2 2^2 + \log_2 2^3</m>.</li>
            </ol>
            <p xml:id="auto_qgobb05m">What do you notice?</p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight xml:id="auto_4fsqkrlm">
        <p xml:id="auto_c7bsiw9y">
            Since:
            <me>
                2^2 \times 2^3 = 2^{2+3} = 2^5
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_edl1dlqj">
            Taking logarithm base <m>2</m>:
            <me>
                \log_2 (2^2 \times 2^3) = \log_2 2^5 = 5
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_7awjhwyy">
            But:
            <me>
                \log_2 2^2 + \log_2 2^3 = 2 + 3 = 5
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wdbh9bbl">
            Therefore,
            <me>
                \log_a (MN) = \log_a M + \log_a N
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_zh1wxvzz">
            This is called the <term>Product Law of Logarithms</term>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_q13nz2w3">
            Logarithms convert multiplication into addition.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <activity xml:id="auto_intro_logs_ratios">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_x4yvk742">
                Repeat the process for division:
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_meicsdiz">Evaluate: <m>5^4 \div 5^2</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_f13madfa">Rewrite as a single power of <m>5</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hzxexxu9">Find: <m>\log_5 (5^4 \div 5^2)</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_p8zi4kon">Compare with: <m>\log_5 5^4 - \log_5 5^2</m>.</li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight xml:id="auto_x9229kmv">
        <p xml:id="auto_0ez7itow">
            Since:
            <me>
                5^4 \div 5^2 = 5^{4-2} = 5^2
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_2fwwpqhe">
            Therefore,
            <me>
                \log_a \left(\frac{M}{N}\right) = \log_a M - \log_a N
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_l84iycc9">
            This is called the <term>Quotient Law of Logarithms</term>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_awrkko0w">
            Logarithms convert division into subtraction.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To apply the learned concepts and procedures to solve varied problems.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners work on a set of problems individually or in pairs. The problems are designed to move from simple classification to application and reasoning.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    The teacher monitors Learners as they work, providing support where needed and encouraging Learners to explain their reasoning using the formal properties discussed in the key takeaways.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_bsp08p2f">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_bq0ax2zz">
                Express as a sum or difference of logarithms and evaluate:
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_kpivg9dc"><m>\log_3 (9 \times 27)</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_c51epjc1"><m>\log_5 \left(\frac{125}{25}\right)</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_il0zsmsk"><m>\log_2 (16 \times 8)</m></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_q8hhlb34">
                a) Using the product law: <me>\log_3 (9 \times 27) = \log_3 9 + \log_3 27 = 2 + 3 = 5</me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zv5gc1ke">
                b) Using the quotient law: <me>\log_5 \left(\frac{125}{25}\right) = \log_5 125 - \log_5 25 = 3 - 2 = 1</me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_27eam3qd">
                c) Using the product law: <me>\log_2 (16 \times 8) = \log_2 16 + \log_2 8 = 4 + 3 = 7</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

